I guess, in the end, all I want is for people to start taking personal responsibility, stop thinking you know what's better for anyone but yourself, and for god's sake, put the fucking shopping cart back in the corral.

Laws are guidelines to punishment for past behaviors in the hope that it will stop future behaviors, and nothing more than that. A law, a decree, an executive order is only as good as the person willing to follow it. And you trust others to follow them every day.

People who say they don't trust others put a lot of trust in others and their willingness to adhere to the social contract. Nothing is stopping anyone from doing whatever they want. Sure, there may be consequences afterwards, but in the moment? Nothing.

"I don't trust society, they're all idiots. I'm the only smart one!" you say, as you get into your car and drive somewhere. Unknowingly, you are trusting in the self-autonomy of other drivers to obey the traffic laws. You do this every day. And you don't think about it.

"I think everyone should/shouldn't get the vaccine"
"I think everyone should/shouldn't get an abortion"
"I think everyone should/shouldn't do drugs"
"I think everyone should/shouldn't own guns"

There's a third option. Let everyone decide for themselves. But that's scary.

May is "Mental Health Awareness Month", but mental health should be an everyday thing. Whether your demons are external or internal, the only way to beat them is to face them, and face them with someone licensed to help you, not with whatever your favorite internet celebrity did.
